{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511729"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11772"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.14,0.04,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4385"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81262"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4385"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66596"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81262"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a four month history of persistent pelvic pain. The pain is especially severe during her menstrual period, and she sometimes has to take time off work to rest. When asked, she mentions that her periods have also been getting heavier. She denies having abnormal vaginal discharge and recently had an STI screen that came back clear. Her most recent cervical screening test was low risk. A urine dipstick indicates that she is not pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal examination and pelvic examination are both normal. She is referred for a transvaginal ultrasound which does not detect any abnormalities, despite a continuation of the same symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following will provide a definitive diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clinical acumen alone","CT abdomen and pelvis","Endometrial biopsy","MRI","Laparoscopy and biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe women\u0027s presentation is likely due to endometriosis indicated by the location of the pain, its relation to the menstrual period and the lack of other findings. It would be appropriate in this scenario to refer the patient for \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopy and biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E of lesions if found. This is the gold standard test for diagnosing endometriosis. The negative ultrasound findings do not rule out endometriosis and further investigations must be done. An MRI may later be used if the endometriosis is identified as deep and its full extent cannot be identified during the laparoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI - \u003C/strong\u003EIncorrect. MRI is not the preferred primary mode of investigation for endometriosis. Rather it would more appropriately be used to assess the extent of deep endometriosis, especially if the history suggested the bowel or bladder was affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Ehas been suggested as a means of diagnosing endometriosis where some studies have shown an increased number of endometrial nerve fibres in women with endometriosis compared to women without endometriosis. However, this would only provide indirect suggestive evidence of such a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT of abdomen and pelvis \u003C/strong\u003E- Incorrect. CT scan should not be the primary investigation for diagnosing endometriosis. It may be used to assess the extent of deep endometriosis if MRI is not available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eclinical acumen \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be relied on more often than it is in today\u0027s medicine, the severity of this patient\u0027s symptoms suggests that whilst endometriosis is the likely diagnosis, further investigation is required to confirm the diagnosis and rule out more sinister pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Histological examination of biopsied tissue is the gold standard for diagnosing endometriosis."],"references":["Australian clinical practice guideline for the diagnosis and management of endometriosis (2021). RANZCOG, Melbourne, Australia"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66596"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66596"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T09:36:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T09:36:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4385"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81262"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"